{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_lily_ver01/data/sn78002169/00279558856/1945081001/0478.xml":{"full_text":"OPA CHIEF WINS\nSIGNAL VICTORY\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 9.\u2014 (U.fi)\nOPA Chief Chester Bowles won a\nclear-cut victory on reconversion\npolicy today when President Tru\nman, resolving his first inter\nagency quarrel, told War Produc\ntion Chairman J. A. Krug that gov\nerment controls over civilian pro\nduction must continue undiminish\ned.\nIn a mildly-administered bpt\nnonetheless firm rebuke to Krug,\nthe President said that WPB not\nonly must stay on the job but also\nmust continue to carry out a five\npoint program for controlled re\nconversion. Krug reportedly had\nwanted to scrap all possible Fed\neral controls and give WPB only\na minor role in the reconversion\npicture.\nMr. Truman restated the admin\nistration\u2019! belief that all controls\nshould be lifted as soon as possible,,\nbut added that \u201cthe government\nhas a major responsibility to as\nsist in the achievement of an pr\nderly transition from war produc\ntion to civilian production.\u201d\nThat, in substance, is Bowles\u2019\nposition.\nThe President called both Krug\nand Bowles on the carpet before\nreleasing his letter. Also present\nwas War Mobilization Director\nJohn W. Snyder.\nAfter the White House confer\nence Krug said that WPB \u201cwill\nstay on the job as long as there\nis any need for its services.\u201d He\ninterpreted the President\u2019s letter\nas a request that WPB see the re\nconversion job through \u201cbecause it\nis the only government agency hav\ning extensive experience with in\ndustrial production.\u201d\nThe dispute\u2019between Bowles and\nKrug was made sharper by the ap\nparent imminence of Japan s de\nfeat. Krug argued that WPB is\nessentially a war agency, that it\nhas no place in reconversion, and\nthat civilian production would pro\ngress better if WPB controls and\nregulations were eliminated.\nBowles contends that material\nand inventory controls must re\nmain so long as the government's\nstabilization program, including\npricing and rationing, is in effect.\nHe believes that if industry is giv\nen a clear field now, there will be\ndanger of inflation and economic\ndislocations.\n-V\nFour Killed, Many Hurt\nIn Tennessee Blast\nMILAN, Tenn., Aug. 9.\u2014 (JP)\nFour persons were killed and\nothers injured in an explosion at\nthe Milan Ordance plant here to\nday.\nLt. Col. Kenneth M. Haber, ccf 1\nmanding officer, said the explo\nsion occurred at 1:20 p.m. on one\nof the ammunition lines.\nHe said the extent nor cause of\nthe damage was not immediately\nascertained.\n\u2014-v\u2014\nBUY WAR BONDS AND STAMPS\nSoviets Hold Meetings\nOn Declaration Of War\nLONDON, Aug. 9.\u2014(A>)\u2014Patriot\nmeetings in Soviet territory in\nEastern Siberia followed Russia\u2019s\ndeclaration of war upon Japan, the\nMoscow radio said tonight.\nThe meetings here held in Kha\nborvsk, from where one Soviet at\ntack was launched, Komsomolsk on\nthe Amur river below Khabarovsk,\nin the Sakhalin oil fields and coal\nmines area, and the Kamatchka\nfishing combines, the broadcast\nsaid.\n-V\nSTAR ANNOUNCER SPEAKS\nLONDON, Aug. 9.\u2014(JP)\u2014Tile Mos\ncow Radio\u2019s star announcer, Yu.f\nLevitan, read tonight\u2019s first Rus\nsian communique on the Japan\nese war, the Soviet monitor said.\nYuri\u2019s voice is generally reserved\nfor special occasions.\nW. M. TODD\n613 Castle Street Phone 5251\nArmour\u2019s Cloverbloom, Mor- reamery\nreU\u2019s Yorkshire Farm, Swift\u2019s D ||ll*S J Qsa lit\nBrookfield, Kingan's Reliabls. DUIIvlf 4/C IDl\nOLD FASHIONED\nCHEESE, lb.37c\nCOLLARD, (No. 2 1-2 can)\nGREENS.18C\nBUSH (No. 2 1-2 can)\nPORK BEANS 17c\nLG. JAR\nCarrots Peas 17c\nSUNLAND\nCOCOANUT,pkg.31c\nRED KIDNEY\nBEANS, No. 1 can 9c\nSOY (No. 2 can)\nBEANS 2 for 15c\nSWEET MEADOW\nCORN, No. 2 can 136\nSablsco M6MEV MA1P CKAHAMS~i>c\nHablsco SHttEBftEB WHEAT. 12c\nNabisco 100 per cent BRAN, pkg. 10c\n,,V Small He\nLIIA Large 26c\nLIFEBUOY 8c\nHEAL